Part 1 — The marketing input is right, and here's what it changes
Your marketing contact named five gaps. Each one is real. But they're not a flat list — they fall into three categories with different urgency, and treating them uniformly would dilute their force. Here's how I'm sorting them.
Category A — Things that change the product
Brand and cultural relevance for Barbados specifically. This is the most important of the five, and it's the one that's been most absent from our conversations. The platform we've been building is generic — "tournament platform with sponsor metrics, works anywhere." That's the right architectural choice for a long-term company. But the first instance of this platform, in August, in Barbados, isn't a generic event. It's a Caribbean gaming convention with specific cultural texture, specific aesthetic expectations, specific community dynamics. If MAJHEVENTS shows up looking like a Silicon Valley SaaS product transplanted to Bridgetown, it will feel imported, and "imported" in a Caribbean cultural context reads as not-for-us. That's a brand failure that no amount of feature completeness fixes.
What this changes in the plan: The visual design, copy, and tone of the Barbados-instance UI must be culturally calibrated. This is not a "polish" task we squeeze in at the end. It's a workstream that runs in parallel with engineering for the final 8 weeks. Specifically, between the Barbados team and you, someone needs to own brand expression — color, typography, photography choices, copy voice, music in promo videos, who appears on the marketing site, what the event hashtag actually feels like. The architecture is universal; the brand layer is local.
This is also where you have an advantage I'd been underweighting. You're Barbadian (or at least connected to the Caribbean — correct me if I'm wrong). You know what flat-imported feels like and what culturally-resonant feels like. A pure tech founder couldn't do this. You can. The work isn't "hire a brand agency"; it's "make sure the platform's first impression is yours, not generic."
The event experience itself. The marketing person flagged that we've been building "software first, experience second" and that events don't work that way. She's right that this is a gap, but I want to push back on the implication.
For August specifically, the order has to be: software works → experience is delightful. If the software doesn't work, the experience is "we couldn't process tournament registrations and the bracket didn't show up correctly." No amount of vibe rescues that. So the rule is: software has to be correct by mid-July, but the experience design starts NOW and compounds. They're not competing priorities; they're parallel workstreams with different completion deadlines.
What this changes: We add an "event experience design" workstream to the plan, owned by you (with input from the Barbados team), running parallel to the engineering work. Concrete outputs: the player check-in flow walkthrough, the spectator first-experience video, the sponsor-arrival walkthrough, the moments of intentional delight (the "this feels live" moments). These get specified now, built into the platform alongside the engineering, and rehearsed in July.
Category B — Things that change the go-to-market
Audience acquisition: how the first 100-500 people are acquired. This is a real strategic gap and it's been entirely absent from our conversations because I've treated "Barbados is the customer" as if Barbados means the convention organizer, not the convention attendees. Those are different problems. The convention organizer signed up. The 500 attendees haven't.
What this changes: A new workstream — "audience acquisition for Barbados attendees" — that needs to exist independently of the platform engineering. This is marketing/community work, not engineering work, but the platform has to support it. Specifically: the platform needs to have public-facing pages that work for marketing (event landing page, share-friendly URLs, social-card metadata, organizer-supplied content blocks). Right now we have backend tournament logic; we don't have a marketing surface that the Barbados team can drive traffic to.
This isn't 6 weeks of engineering. It's maybe 3-5 days of focused work on the public-facing event page, plus the Barbados team's actual marketing motion (paid ads, community partnerships, influencer activations, whatever they're already planning). But the days have to happen, and they have to happen earlier than I'd implicitly assumed.
Sponsor pipeline beyond projections. The marketing person is right: investor-readable sponsor projections are not the same as confirmed sponsorships. For the convention itself to succeed financially in a way that compounds (you mentioned MAJHEVENTS taking 25% of sponsorships), there needs to be a real outreach motion now, not in July. The platform's sponsor metrics work (T-053 area) is intended to make the value proposition concrete, but the actual sales conversations have to happen in parallel.
What this changes: Acknowledge in the plan that sponsor outreach is a workstream owned by either you or the Barbados team, not by engineering, but with an engineering dependency: the sponsor metrics demo (a clickable mockup or live data on a real test event) needs to exist by end of June so that sponsor conversations from July onward can show, not tell. This puts a soft deadline on T-046 (sponsor metrics dashboard) that we hadn't articulated.
Category C — Things that don't change the plan but expose real risk
Execution complexity vs team capacity. The marketing person asked what happens if one piece fails. That's the most important question in this entire feedback, and it doesn't get a structural fix; it gets a protocol fix. We need to articulate, in advance:
What workstreams exist, and who owns each one
What's the minimum viable outcome for each workstream by August
What gets cut first if one workstream is in trouble (kill-switch protocol)
What the abort condition looks like (when do we tell Barbados we can't deliver, if ever)
This is in Part 4 of this document. But I want to name it here: the marketing person identified the single most likely failure mode of the plan, which is that you're carrying too many simultaneous workstreams alone. The honest answer isn't "I'll work harder." It's "here are the workstreams, here's what gets cut first, here's the minimum viable thing for each."
Proof of demand at scale. This is partially valid and partially the wrong frame for where we are. The truthful answer is: proof of demand at scale doesn't exist for MAJHEVENTS yet, and proving it before August is unrealistic. The validation event IS Barbados. We're not building toward "we proved demand at 10 events"; we're building toward "we proved demand at one event, learned what worked, and have a credible plan for events 2-10."
This is the right size of bet for a bootstrap-stage company with one paying customer. A VC would push back; you're not raising VC. Hold the position.
What CAN be done before August: smaller validation signals. Tournament-organizer waitlist for events 2-5 (do other organizers want this when they hear about Barbados?). Sponsor expression-of-interest letters for the platform itself (separate from Barbados sponsors — do regional sponsors want this concept?). Pre-Barbados attendee waitlist (do gamers in the region want to come?). None of these are "demand at scale," but they're directional indicators that strengthen the post-Barbados pitch.
What changes in your operating frame as a result of this input
Three additions to how you should think about the next 14 weeks:
1. There are now three workstreams, not one. Engineering, brand/experience, and go-to-market. They run in parallel. They have different owners (you might be all three, but that has to be explicit). They have different deadlines. The plan in Part 4 reflects this.
2. The Barbados team is a co-builder, not just a customer. They have local context, audience, and brand instinct that you cannot replicate from the engineering side. Schedule the discovery call (T-080) with this expanded agenda — not just "what do you need from the platform," but "what's the brand, what's the audience acquisition motion, what's the sponsor pipeline, what's the feel of the event." They've probably already thought about most of this. You inherit their work; you don't recreate it.
3. The "stability and durability" strategic frame still holds. Marketing input is making the plan richer, not changing its core. We're still bootstrapping to Barbados, still owning the differentiated layer, still avoiding venture capital pressure. We're just being more honest about what "running an event" actually requires beyond "building a platform."
